Boundary Conditions and Deformations: 
  Higher-Spin Theory 
Now we are ready to present our concrete proposal by considering various
boundary conditions  for the bulk fields that appear in the action
(). First we will consider the large- duals of
the bulk theory which means that we discuss only the tree level
bulk action. In section , we will discuss the effects of bulk loops on the
higher-spin gauge symmetry.

Large- duals 

The free  Supersymmetric  vector model 

To obtain the free  Supersymmetric  vector model
in the boundary we consider the irregular  boundary
condition for  and the regular  one for .
Making also an appropriate choice for the boundary condition of
the bulk fermion, as explained in Section , we preserve
supersymmetry. Moreover, as we will argue in Section  these
boundary conditions will not break the higher-spin gauge symmetry even
after bulk loops are taken into account.

The strongly coupled  Supersymmetric
 vector model 
In this case, we use the regular  boundary condition
for  and the irregular  one for . Then,
with the opposite choice from above for the boundary conditions of
the bulk fermions we still preserve supersymmetry. However, now
the boundary "spin-zero" current multiplet cannot be represented
by free fields due to the specific parity assignments. This  theory corresponds
to the large- limit of the IR fixed point of the 
vector model. The reason is that, as we will argue in Section , the
specific boundary conditions chosen here will break the higher-spin
gauge symmetry for subleading- when bulk loops are taken into
account. In this way the currents in the boundary theory will acquire
anomalous dimensions of order . 

Deformations 

Next, we consider deformations of the boundary Lagrangian.

Mass deformations 

The simplest deformation of the free  theory that one
could consider is a boundary condition corresponding to adding a mass
term for elementary fields in the boundary theory. For example, a
boundary fermion mass term will clearly lead to an infrared theory
containing only currents built out of the elementary bosons , once  corrections are taken into account. From the
bulk point of view, this physics should be reproduced classically, by a suitable "domain wall".  In particular, one must be able to see
that all higher spin bulk fields that were coupled to boundary operators
involving fermions (i.e.,  and  and their higher-spin
partners) are made massive by the choice of boundary condition. In
this way, one is left with the spectrum of the  bosonic higher
spin theory. Similarly, a boundary boson mass term should leave only
the fermionic currents in the boundary theory, or in the bulk, only
 and its higher-spin partners. 

A marginal double-trace perturbation 

Given the established connection between the Legendre transformation and double trace operators, it is clearly of interest to study these in the present context. There are two distinct choices that we will identify. 

First, a (classically) marginal deformation of the free boundary theory is 
  
  This is supersymmetric along the line  in which case it corresponds to the
  deformation . It is easily seen
  that this deformation violates parity. It is interesting
  to ask where the deformation () leads the free
   vector model to, for large values of the couplings ,
   and large . One way to answer
  this is to recall that
  () can actually be imposed via an appropriate
  boundary condition on the bulk fields. In the notation of the
previous section this is
   
We now see that in the supersymmetric case the limit
of large coupling constant and large  just leads to the strongly coupled
theory of Subsection . Thus, even though the deformation
() breaks parity, at large  we end up with an
 supersymmetric theory.

It is also possible that the deformation () is actually exactly  marginal. This sort of possibility
was mentioned in Ref. in the bosonic theory, where it
was noted that AdS apparently remains a solution for any value of
the coupling . In
the present case, the situation is even better: eq.   ()
is a deformation of a free  CFT and thus marginality can be
investigated perturbatively. We are not aware of literature related
directly to this question, but it should not be too difficult an issue
to settle. 

A supersymmetry breaking deformation 

Another interesting "double-trace" deformation of the free
theory is
 
This is a closer analogue to the double trace deformation considered for the bosonic theory.
It corresponds to the boundary conditions 

^(-) _2=g_2^(-) _2, ^(+) _1=g_1^(+) _1,
u_-=-g_3 u_+ ,
which of course break supersymmetry. 
corresponds to a relevant deformation of the free  fixed
point while the  deformation looks irrelevant from an RG
point of view. Again, we can ask where the deformation
() leads the free boundary theory to, for large
values of the couplings and large . This can be answered using information from the
bulk. Namely, we see from the boundary conditions ()
that for large values of the coupling constants one is apparently led to the
strongly coupled theory of Subsection  again! This time,
the boundary conditions for the scalars are parity preserving
while the one for the fermion is parity non-preserving. The
remarkable result is that despite the fact the the deformation
() breaks supersymmetry, at large  we recover an
 supersymmetric theory,  at its strongly
coupled fixed point. This is perhaps not as surprising as it seems, as
the RG interpretation of the deformation () is rather
unusual. Indeed, due
to the structure of the Wess-Zumino multiplet, one may view the free boundary
theory as being "half at the UV fixed point" (the part involving the
bosons) while the other half is at its "IR fixed point" (the part
involving the fermions). 

Subleading- and the breaking of higher-spin gauge
symmetry 
In the previous subsection we argued that the tree level 
 higher-spin theory on AdS leads to two  boundary
3d CFTs whose composite operators have exactly  the same
spectrum of dimensions. The only property that distinguishes the
two boundary theories, at large ,  is the parity assignment of the operators in
the supermultiplets. One choice of parity assignments leads to the
free  vector model while the other choice leads to a
strongly coupled version of the  vector model. The
generating functionals of the two theories are related by a
Legendre transform.

The distinction between the two
theories should become more evident when considering bulk loop
corrections or, equivalenty corrections subleading in  in the boundary theory. 
In other words, we expect that starting with the boundary action
() and considering the boundary conditions that
lead to the free boundary theory, bulk loops do 
not break the higher-spin gauge symmetry. That is,  the bulk
higher-spin fields remain massless while the corresponding boundary
currents remain conserved. On the other hand, considering the
boundary conditions that lead to the strongly coupled boundary
theory we expect that the bulk loops will render the higher-spin
fields massive (Higgsing) and the corresponding boundary currents
non-conserved.

The mechanism by which the phenomenon described above takes place
is a generalization of the mechanism discussed in for
the case of the minimal bosonic higher-spin theory on AdS. The basic physics arises from the fact that a representation that is massive from the bulk point of view satisfies
 
as . This can be taken to imply that in order for a spin  field to become massive, there must be a suitable Goldstone mode transforming as , it must be of the correct parity, and there must be a suitable coupling present in the bulk effective action.

Here we elucidate this argument further by discussing it from the boundary
point of view. Conformal invariance requires that a boundary spin 
current  with dimension  is
also conserved. Non-conservation of this current appears in the
form of an anomalous dimension, . Let us
assume that . Then, the
non-conservation of a boundary current means that there is an operator equation of the form
